{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Employment figures should be HMRC data & not interviews of 40,000 households",
        "additional_details": "HMRC have every taxpayer work in the UK on record.  They use that to identify everyone\u2019s salary and allocate tax codes.  These tax codes could therefore be grouped together to give accurate figures as to who is employed, rather than use interviews of 40,000 households.\r\nMembers of Parliament would then be quoting more accurate employment figures to the House, rather than ones based on 40,000 interviews.",
        "background": "\u201cOutput from the Labour Force Survey (LFS) is quarterly since 1992. Each quarter\u2019s sample is made up of 5 waves.\r\nThe sample is made up of approximately 40,000 responding UK households and 100,000 individuals per quarter.\"",
